'''Kimitezuri''' (君手摩, also known as '''Kimite''' (君手) or '''Kimitecchi''' (君てっ, きみって)) is a goddess in {{ill|Ryukyuan Shinto|ja|琉球神道|12=draft}}. According to tradition, she is regarded as the {{ill|guardian deity|ja|守護神|12=draft}} of the {{ill|Ryukyu Kingdom|ja|琉球王国|12=draft}}, presiding over the {{ill|sea|ja|海|12=draft}} and the {{ill|sun|ja|太陽|12=draft}}. It is believed that she descends at moments of crisis for the kingdom. She is said to reside in {{ill|Nirai Kanai|ja|ニライカナイ|12=draft}}, a mystical realm described as being in the depths of the sea, beyond the horizon, or underground. During the enthronement ceremony of a new ruler, she is believed to possess the {{ill|Kikoe-ōgimi|ja|聞得大君|12=draft}}, the highest-Ranking priestess of the kingdom. Historically, she has been closely associated with {{ill|Kinmamun|ja|キンマモン|12=draft}}.

The earliest historical record of Kimitezuri as a deity appears in the ''{{ill|Chūzan Seikan|ja|中山世鑑|12=draft}}'', compiled by {{ill|Shō Genken|ja|向象賢|12=draft}} (also known as {{ill|Haneji Chōshū|ja|羽地朝秀|12=draft}}). However, some scholars argue that "Kimitezuri" may not refer to a specific deity but rather a religious ritual. The word "Kimite" (君) traditionally refers to a {{ill|Noro|ja|ノロ|12=draft}}, a female shaman responsible for religious ceremonies in Ryukyuan worship, while "Tesuri" (手摩) means rubbing hands together in prayer. Other historical records also describe Kimitezuri as a ceremonial practice rather than a divine figure.

