[[ja:君手摩]] [[sn:Kimitezuri]] [[sn:imitezuri]] [[Category:Religion in the Ryukyu Islands]] [[Category:琉球の神]] <!--jawiki derived wikidata interwikis--> [[zh:君手摩]]

'''Kimitezuri''' (君手摩, also known as '''Kimite''' (君手) or '''Kimitecchi''' (君てっ, きみって)) is a goddess in [[:en:Ryukyuan religion|Ryukyuan Shinto]]. According to tradition, she is regarded as the {{ill|Guardian deities|lt=Guardian deities|lt=Guardian deity|ja|守護神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/guardian deity|qq=}} of the [[:en:Ryukyu Kingdom|Ryukyu Kingdom]], presiding over the [[:en:Sea|sea]] and the [[:en:Sun|sun]]. It is believed that she descends at moments of crisis for the kingdom. She is said to reside in {{ill|Nirai Kanai|ja|ニライカナイ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nirai Kanai|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}, a mystical realm described as being in the depths of the sea, beyond the horizon, or underground. During the enthronement ceremony of a new ruler, she is believed to possess the [[:en:Kikoe-ōgimi|Kikoe-ōgimi]], the highest-Ranking priestess of the kingdom. Historically, she has been closely associated with {{ill|Kinmamun|ja|キンマモン|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kinmamun|qq=}}.
The earliest historical record of Kimitezuri as a deity appears in the ''[[:en:Chūzan Seikan|Chūzan Seikan]]'', compiled by {{ill|Shō Genken|ja|向象賢|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shō Genken|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 羽地朝秀}} (also known as [[:en:Shō Shōken|Haneji Chōshū]]). However, some scholars argue that "Kimitezuri" may not refer to a specific deity but rather a religious ritual. The word "Kimite" (君) traditionally refers to a [[:en:Noro (priestess)|Noro]], a female shaman responsible for religious ceremonies in Ryukyuan worship, while "Tesuri" (手摩) means rubbing hands together in prayer. Other historical records also describe Kimitezuri as a ceremonial practice rather than a divine figure.
