'''Kimitezuri''' (君手摩, also known as '''Kimite''' (君手) or '''Kimitecchi''' (君てっ, きみって)) is a goddess in {{ill|Ryukyuan religion|en|Ryukyuan religion|qid=Q892785|lt=Ryukyuan Shinto|1=Ryukyuan religion}}. According to tradition, she is regarded as the {{ill|Guardian deities|lt=Guardian deities|lt=Guardian deity|ja|守護神|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/guardian deity|qq=}} of the {{ill|Ryukyu Kingdom|en|Ryukyu Kingdom|qid=Q28025|lt=Ryukyu Kingdom|1=Ryukyu Kingdom}}, presiding over the {{ill|Sea|en|Sea|qid=Q165|lt=sea|1=Sea}} and the {{ill|Sun|en|Sun|qid=Q525|lt=sun|1=Sun}}. It is believed that she descends at moments of crisis for the kingdom. She is said to reside in {{ill|Nirai Kanai|ja|ニライカナイ|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nirai Kanai|comment=changed title based on wikidata|1=Nirai Kanai|qid=Q24885856}}, a mystical realm described as being in the depths of the sea, beyond the horizon, or underground. During the enthronement ceremony of a new ruler, she is believed to possess the {{ill|Kikoe-ōgimi|en|Kikoe-ōgimi|qid=Q11611193|lt=Kikoe-ōgimi|1=Kikoe-ōgimi}}, the highest-Ranking priestess of the kingdom. Historically, she has been closely associated with {{ill|Kinmamun|ja|キンマモン|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kinmamun|1=kinmanmontomo|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q24867498}}.

The earliest historical record of Kimitezuri as a deity appears in the ''{{ill|Chūzan Seikan|en|Chūzan Seikan|qid=Q8015936|lt=Chūzan Seikan|1=Chūzan Seikan}}'', compiled by {{ill|Shō Genken|ja|向象賢|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shō Genken|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 羽地朝秀|1=Shō Shōken|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q843010}} (also known as {{ill|Shō Shōken|en|Shō Shōken|qid=Q843010|lt=Haneji Chōshū|1=Shō Shōken}}). However, some scholars argue that "Kimitezuri" may not refer to a specific deity but rather a religious ritual. The word "Kimite" (君) traditionally refers to a {{ill|Noro (priestess)|en|Noro (priestess)|qid=Q11325791|lt=Noro|1=Noro (priestess)}}, a female shaman responsible for religious ceremonies in Ryukyuan worship, while "Tesuri" (手摩) means rubbing hands together in prayer. Other historical records also describe Kimitezuri as a ceremonial practice rather than a divine figure.

